Task 1: Change File Permissions with chmod
Understanding Permission Basics
Linux file permissions consist of three types of access for three categories of users:

Read (r): Permission to view file contents or list directory contents
Write (w): Permission to modify file contents or create/delete files in directory
Execute (x): Permission to run file as program or access directory
The three categories of users are:

Owner (u): The user who owns the file
Group (g): Users belonging to the file's group
Others (o): All other users on the system
Subtask 1.1: View Current Permissions
# Display detailed file permissions
ls -l

# Display permissions in numeric format
stat -c "%a %n" *

# Understand the permission format
echo "Permission format explanation:"
echo "drwxrwxrwx = directory with full permissions"
echo "-rw-r--r-- = regular file with read/write for owner, read for group and others"
Subtask 1.2: Using Symbolic Mode with chmod
# Add execute permission for owner
chmod u+x test_script.sh

# Remove write permission for group and others
chmod go-w file1.txt

# Set specific permissions using symbolic notation
chmod u=rw,g=r,o=r file2.txt

# Add read and execute permissions for all users to directory
chmod a+rx testdir1

# Verify changes
ls -l
Subtask 1.3: Using Numeric Mode with chmod
# Set permissions using octal notation
# 755 = rwxr-xr-x (owner: rwx, group: r-x, others: r-x)
chmod 755 test_script.sh

# 644 = rw-r--r-- (owner: rw-, group: r--, others: r--)
chmod 644 file1.txt

# 600 = rw------- (owner: rw-, group: ---, others: ---)
chmod 600 secret.txt

# 777 = rwxrwxrwx (full permissions for all)
chmod 777 testdir2

# Verify the changes
ls -l
stat -c "%a %n" *
Subtask 1.4: Recursive Permission Changes
# Create subdirectories and files for testing
mkdir -p testdir1/subdir1/subdir2
touch testdir1/file_in_dir.txt
touch testdir1/subdir1/nested_file.txt

# Apply permissions recursively
chmod -R 755 testdir1

# Verify recursive changes
find testdir1 -exec ls -ld {} \;
Task 2: Set File Ownership with chown
Understanding Ownership Concepts
Every file and directory in Linux has:

Owner: A specific user account
Group: A specific group that can access the file
Subtask 2.1: View Current Ownership
# Display current ownership information
ls -l

# Show detailed ownership with user and group IDs
ls -n

# Display current user and group information
whoami
groups
id
Subtask 2.2: Create Test Users and Groups
# Create test group (requires sudo)
sudo groupadd testgroup

# Add current user to the test group
sudo usermod -a -G testgroup $USER

# Verify group membership
groups $USER
Subtask 2.3: Change File Ownership
# Change group ownership of a file
sudo chown :testgroup file1.txt

# Change both user and group ownership (if you have another user)
# Note: This example uses the current user
sudo chown $USER:testgroup file2.txt

# Change ownership recursively
sudo chown -R $USER:testgroup testdir1

# Verify ownership changes
ls -l
ls -ld testdir1
Subtask 2.4: Using chgrp Command
# Change group ownership using chgrp
sudo chgrp testgroup secret.txt

# Change group ownership recursively
sudo chgrp -R testgroup testdir2

# Verify changes
ls -l
Task 3: Practice umask and ACL Configurations
Subtask 3.1: Understanding and Configuring umask
# Display current umask value
umask

# Display umask in symbolic format
umask -S

# Create a test file with current umask
touch umask_test1.txt
ls -l umask_test1.txt

# Change umask to be more restrictive
umask 077

# Create another test file
touch umask_test2.txt
ls -l umask_test2.txt

# Change umask to be less restrictive
umask 022

# Create third test file
touch umask_test3.txt
ls -l umask_test3.txt

# Compare the three files
echo "Comparing files created with different umask values:"
ls -l umask_test*.txt
Subtask 3.2: Permanent umask Configuration
# View current umask setting in profile
echo "Current umask in .bashrc:"
grep -n umask ~/.bashrc || echo "No umask found in .bashrc"

# Add custom umask to .bashrc (backup first)
cp ~/.bashrc ~/.bashrc.backup

# Add umask setting
echo "" >> ~/.bashrc
echo "# Custom umask setting for lab" >> ~/.bashrc
echo "umask 027" >> ~/.bashrc

# Verify the addition
tail -3 ~/.bashrc
Subtask 3.3: Working with Access Control Lists (ACLs)
# Check if ACL is supported on the filesystem
getfacl --version

# Create test files for ACL demonstration
touch acl_test1.txt acl_test2.txt
echo "ACL test content" > acl_test1.txt

# View current ACL
getfacl acl_test1.txt

# Set ACL permissions for specific user
setfacl -m u:$USER:rw acl_test1.txt

# Set ACL permissions for group
setfacl -m g:testgroup:r acl_test1.txt

# Set default ACL for directory
mkdir acl_testdir
setfacl -d -m u:$USER:rwx acl_testdir
setfacl -d -m g:testgroup:rx acl_testdir

# View ACL settings
getfacl acl_test1.txt
getfacl acl_testdir

# Create file in directory with default ACL
touch acl_testdir/inherited_file.txt
getfacl acl_testdir/inherited_file.txt
Subtask 3.4: Advanced ACL Operations
# Remove specific ACL entry
setfacl -x u:$USER acl_test1.txt

# Remove all ACL entries
setfacl -b acl_test2.txt

# Copy ACL from one file to another
setfacl -m u:$USER:rw acl_test2.txt
getfacl acl_test2.txt | setfacl --set-file=- acl_test1.txt

# Verify ACL copy
getfacl acl_test1.txt
getfacl acl_test2.txt

# Set ACL with mask
setfacl -m m:r acl_test1.txt
getfacl acl_test1.txt
Practical Scenarios and Troubleshooting
Scenario 1: Web Server File Permissions
# Create a mock web directory structure
mkdir -p ~/webserver/{public_html,logs,config}
touch ~/webserver/public_html/index.html
touch ~/webserver/logs/access.log
touch ~/webserver/config/server.conf

# Set appropriate permissions for web server
chmod 755 ~/webserver
chmod 755 ~/webserver/public_html
chmod 644 ~/webserver/public_html/index.html
chmod 755 ~/webserver/logs
chmod 644 ~/webserver/logs/access.log
chmod 700 ~/webserver/config
chmod 600 ~/webserver/config/server.conf

# Verify the setup
find ~/webserver -exec ls -ld {} \;
Scenario 2: Shared Directory Setup
# Create shared directory
mkdir ~/shared_project
chmod 775 ~/shared_project
sudo chgrp testgroup ~/shared_project

# Set sticky bit for shared directory
chmod +t ~/shared_project

# Set SGID bit for group inheritance
chmod g+s ~/shared_project

# Verify special permissions
ls -ld ~/shared_project

# Test file creation in shared directory
touch ~/shared_project/team_file.txt
ls -l ~/shared_project/
Common Troubleshooting Commands
# Find files with specific permissions
find ~/lab4_permissions -perm 644

# Find files owned by specific user
find ~/lab4_permissions -user $USER

# Find files with SUID/SGID bits set
find ~/lab4_permissions -perm /6000

# Check for files with no group or user
find ~/lab4_permissions -nouser -o -nogroup

# Display files with ACLs
find ~/lab4_permissions -exec getfacl {} \; 2>/dev/null | grep -l "user::"
